Get all user client permission group frontend pages with pagination and filters.

Get all frontend pages accessible to the current user through their permission groups.

This endpoint combines:
1. Pages directly assigned to user through UserPermissionGroupFrontendPage
2. Pages assigned to permission groups through PermissionGroupFrontendPage

The response includes nested details about:
- Frontend page information
- User client permission group (which includes client, user, and permission group details)

get.description:
Get all frontend pages accessible to the current user through their client products.

This endpoint returns pages directly assigned to user through UserClientProductPage
and validates that the following conditions are also satisfied:

1. Page belongs to Product (-> ProductPage)
2. Product belongs to Client (-> ClientProduct)
3. User is assigned to Client (-> UserClient)
4. User is assigned to Product through Client (-> UserClientProduct)

The response is a list of UserClientProductPage and includes base nested responses for:
- Page
- Product
- Client
- User

get.description:
Returns current facility gates with shipment, crane operator note, and heating value,
along with the waiting trucks at the facility.

- gates:
--> shipment: most recent un-deleted shipment at that gate with null or non-ash waste code
--> note: crane operator note for the shipment OR waste code description
--> min/ heating value: from waste properties (customised -> original)
--> is_risky: true if any waste generator (via contract) is flagged risky
--> no time limit or checks for if that shipment has left already

- waiting_trucks:
--> most recent 20 shipments at a facility with no exit timestamp and no gate assigned,
    excluding ash waste codes, entry timestamp must be within last 3 hours

- high_severity_analyses_response:
--> returns 5 custom schemas, based on the most recent Analyses for that facility
    where waste_code is contam and toxicity_risk_level or explosive_risk_level is high
--> no time cut off

Returns current facility deliveries with crane operator note and heating value, and detected contaminants.

For each gate, we start by getting the latest 3 waiting Truck records (not Shipment!).

Remember that a Truck row will be generated with the current state if it does not match the previous
row's state -- consider these example "rows", in order from most recent to oldest:

a. Simple delivery -> truck arrives, delivers, leaves:
1. Truck: has_truck=False (-> gate is empty; truck has left again)
2. Truck: has_truck=True (-> truck arrives and delivers waste)
3. Truck: has_truck=False (-> gate is empty; truck has not arrived yet)

b. License plate/truck detection blocked by passing obstacle:
1. Truck: has_truck=True (-> actually same truck & delivery as before, just "rediscovered")
2. Truck: has_truck=False (-> gate is NOT empty, but camera is blocked so toggles new row)
3. Truck: has_truck=True (-> this is the original truck delivery. arrival time within 5 minutes of Row 1)

We then return a list of objects with the following schema, one per gate:
- is_active: bool -> either is_open or was_recently_open is True
- is_open: bool -> the most recent Truck entry for this gate has .has_truck=True (-> truck is still there)
- was_recently_open: bool -> no truck currently at gate but the 3rd Truck was at door <5m ago (-> likely camera briefly obscured)
- is_active_analysis: bool -> False. (we don't actually set or use this at the moment)
- contaminants: list[AnalysisResponseDetailed] -> list of detected contaminant Analyses within last 10 minutes
  (via Analysis.waste_code_uid -> is_contaminant)

Returns current facility deliveries with crane operator note and heating value, and detected contaminants.
This endpoint uses the Contaminant table directly instead of Analysis table.

For each gate, we start by getting the latest 3 waiting Truck records (not Shipment!).

Remember that a Truck row will be generated with the current state if it does not match the previous
row's state -- consider these example "rows", in order from most recent to oldest:

a. Simple delivery -> truck arrives, delivers, leaves:
1. Truck: has_truck=False (-> gate is empty; truck has left again)
2. Truck: has_truck=True (-> truck arrives and delivers waste)
3. Truck: has_truck=False (-> gate is empty; truck has not arrived yet)

b. License plate/truck detection blocked by passing obstacle:
1. Truck: has_truck=True (-> actually same truck & delivery as before, just "rediscovered")
2. Truck: has_truck=False (-> gate is NOT empty, but camera is blocked so toggles new row)
3. Truck: has_truck=True (-> this is the original truck delivery. arrival time within 5 minutes of Row 1)

We then return a list of objects with the following schema, one per gate:
- is_active: bool -> either is_open or was_recently_open is True
- is_open: bool -> the most recent Truck entry for this gate has .has_truck=True (-> truck is still there)
- was_recently_open: bool -> no truck currently at gate but the 3rd Truck was at door <5m ago (-> likely camera briefly obscured)
- is_active_analysis: bool -> False. (we don't actually set or use this at the moment)
- contaminants: list[ContaminantBaseResponse] -> list of detected contaminants within last 10 minutes
  (directly from Contaminant table)

Provides all data used by the monitor-verify frontend page.

Returns:
- gate (latest active shipment for each gate, with optional load waste code data)
- mismatched_loads (all loads for the active shipments that don't match the shipment contract waste code)
- waiting trucks (standard across monitor endpoints)

Note that we only consider it a mismatch when shipment and load both have waste codes, and they don't match.
